# Designing a Novel, Publishable EEG Foundation Model: Landscape, White Space, and a Concrete Proposal for PAC-Former v2

## TL;DR
- **The strongest publishable framing is the SSL objective, not the architecture.** Make the paper about **crossfreq-masking as a pretraining objective that forces directional low-phase→high-amplitude learning**, and present the directional Mean-Vector-Length (MVL) coupling operator as the architectural component that *only* pays off under that objective. This is defensible white space: no EEG model to date uses directional PAC as an attention-replacing operator along a band axis, and no EEG SSL objective reconstructs high-frequency amplitude from low-frequency phase.
- **The tri-axial (space×frequency×time) factorization alone is NOT novel enough to carry a paper** — factorized space/time attention is standard (CBraMod, Brant, EEGPT), and an explicit frequency/band axis now exists (BandVQ, Uni-NTFM, EEGFormer). The novelty must live in the *frequency-axis operator* + *objective coupling*, which nobody has done.
- **Frame against benchmark reality:** because AdaBrain-Bench and NeuroAtlas show pretrained EEG FMs do NOT reliably beat supervised models on TUAB (AdaBrain-Bench: "for clinical monitoring tasks, including TUAB, Siena, HMC, and Sleep-EDF, foundation models perform comparable or even worse than traditional models"; EEG-FM-Audit found supervised TS-SEFFNet beats LaBraM/EEGPT by 0.008 F1 on TUAB), the winning story is "mechanism-forcing pretraining beats black-box scaling on imbalanced clinical tasks" — exactly where your first crossfreq results already win (TUAB, CHB-MIT, TUSZ).

## Key Findings

1. **The EEG-FM field has converged on a narrow recipe** — patchify → (VQ) tokenize → masked reconstruction/prediction → factorized or full spatiotemporal transformer. The frequency axis is almost always *implicit* (learned inside the tokenizer) or fused by *symmetric* cross-attention, never a first-class, mechanistically-mixed, directional token dimension.
2. **Directional cross-frequency coupling as an architectural operator is unoccupied white space.** The closest work, ACCNet (Neural Networks 2025), uses cross-frequency coupling as *undirected* graph edges (node-edge GAT, cosine-similarity edges) and is scoped to personalised emotion recognition — not a directional phase→amplitude operator, not an FM, not an SSL objective. No transformer/FM uses MVL/PAC as a differentiable attention substitute.
3. **The crossfreq-masking SSL objective is also unoccupied.** Existing frequency SSL is either phase-swap augmentation (contrastive) or band-wise code masking (BandVQ, within-band) or a phase-aware fidelity loss (NeuroRVQ) — none reconstruct HF amplitude from LF phase. Masked Frequency Modeling exists only in vision.
4. **Your own empirical findings align with a known field lesson:** architecture-side priors under supervised loss don't separate from attention (your 3 failed PAC variants); the payoff requires an objective that demands the mechanism (your crossfreq win). This is exactly the "why now / why not black-box" story reviewers want.
5. **Montage-agnostic spatial encoding is now crowded** (REVE 4D coordinates, DIVER-0 equivariance, LUNA learned queries, CBraMod conv-PE, BrainOmni sensor encoder). Do not make this your headline claim; adopt REVE-style coordinates as sound engineering, not novelty.

## Details

### Part 1 — EEG-native foundation model comparison matrix

**BIOT (Yang et al., NeurIPS 2023).** Tokenization: each channel segmented separately into fixed-length segments → flattened into one long "sentence." Channel axis: channel embedding added per token; handles mismatched channels/variable length/missing values by construction. Positional: relative position embedding + channel embedding. Backbone: linear-attention transformer. SSL: supervised or cross-data (pre)training; joint training across datasets. Frequency: none explicit. Data/benchmarks: EEG (TUAB, TUEV, CHB-MIT), ECG, human activity. Limitation: flattening loses joint spatiotemporal structure; no frequency structure.

**LaBraM (Jiang et al., ICLR 2024 spotlight).** Tokenization: EEG segmented into channel patches; a VQ neural tokenizer (vector-quantized neural spectrum prediction, VQ-NSP) encodes patches into discrete neural codes. Channel axis: token = (channel, time-segment); flexible channel counts. Positional: learnable temporal + channel embeddings (absolute). Backbone: ViT-style transformer. SSL: masked prediction of the discrete codes (BEiT-style). Frequency: the tokenizer predicts Fourier amplitude+phase, so spectral info is inside the codebook, not an axis. Data: 2,534.78 hours across ~20 datasets (figure confirmed by CBraMod). Benchmarks: TUAB, TUEV, emotion, gait. Limitation: fixed absolute PE limits montage transfer; frequency implicit.

**CBraMod (Wang et al., ICLR 2025).** Tokenization: patches (channel × time-segment), each patch a token; 30-second samples. Channel axis: asymmetric conditional/convolutional positional encoding adapts to arbitrary electrode layouts. Backbone: **criss-cross transformer** — parallel spatial-attention (across channels) and temporal-attention (across patches) streams. SSL: patch-based masked EEG reconstruction. Frequency: none explicit. Data: TUEG. Benchmarks: 10 downstream tasks / 12 datasets, SOTA. Limitation: conv-PE needs fine-tuning to transfer ("fixing the pre-trained parameters during training on downstream datasets will lead to a very large performance decline"); no frequency axis; reconstruction favors low-frequency high-amplitude.

**EEGPT (Wang et al., NeurIPS 2024).** Tokenization: patches; ~10M params. Channel axis: local spatio-temporal embedding for cross-device compatibility. Backbone: hierarchical transformer, spatial and temporal processed separately. SSL: **dual** — masked reconstruction + spatio-temporal representation alignment (predict masked-part features against full-signal features, on high-SNR representations rather than raw signal). Frequency: none explicit. Limitation: alignment helps but no spectral/coupling inductive bias.

**Brant / Brant-2 (Zhang et al. 2023; Yuan et al. 2024).** Tokenization: patches p∈R^{Np×C×M}; input encoding adds positional + **frequency information**. Channel axis: dedicated spatial encoder. Backbone: multi-FFN transformer block with temporal encoder (per-channel) then spatial encoder (across channels, same time indices). SSL: masked prediction + forecasting. Frequency: frequency info added to input encoding (feature, not axis). Data: Brant ~1.01TB iEEG / 500M params; Brant-2 ~4TB SEEG(2.3TB)+EEG(1.6TB), 1B params, 15k+ subjects. Benchmarks: seizure detection, sleep, emotion, motor imagery, forecasting, imputation. Limitation: intracranial-origin; frequency not a mixed axis.

**NeuroLM (Jiang et al. 2024/2025).** Tokenization: text-aligned VQ neural tokenizer via vector-quantized temporal-frequency prediction → discrete tokens fed to a frozen-VQ encoder + LLM (GPT). Channel axis: multi-channel via token sequence, explicitly modeling inter-channel dependencies. Backbone: LLM (causal, autoregressive). SSL: autoregressive next-token over EEG tokens; multi-task instruction tuning. Frequency: inside tokenizer. Limitation: LLM-centric; heavy; frequency implicit.

**REVE (El Ouahidi et al., NeurIPS 2025 / 2026).** Tokenization: linear patch embedding of overlapping temporal patches per channel. Channel axis: **4D positional encoding from true 3D electrode coordinates (x,y,z) + temporal patch index**, Fourier-embedded, Gaussian-noise-augmented → arbitrary montage/length without fixed lookup tables. Backbone: transformer encoder, MAE. SSL: masked autoencoding (contiguous block masking across space+time), L1 raw reconstruction + secondary global-token attention-pooling task. Frequency: none explicit. Data: "over 60,000 hours of EEG data from 92 datasets spanning 25,000 subjects, representing the largest EEG pretraining effort to date." Benchmarks: 10 tasks incl. seizure, sleep, MI, emotion, cognitive load; leads TUAB in NeuroAtlas. Limitation: raw reconstruction bias; no spectral/coupling objective; **directly relevant prior art for your montage-agnostic angle**.

**EEGFormer (Chen et al. 2024).** Tokenization: FFT to frequency domain → frequency patchification; channel-independent encoding. Backbone: encoder-decoder transformer with channel-wise VQ. SSL: vector-quantized masked reconstruction; interpretable discrete codebook. Frequency: patchified frequency features (a frequency axis of sorts, but channel-independent and symmetric). Data: ~1.7TB. Benchmarks: TUSZ, neonatal seizure (~15.8%/14.1% AUPRC gains). Limitation: channel-independence ignores inter-channel coupling; no cross-frequency mechanism.

**Neuro-GPT (Cui et al. 2023).** Conv EEG encoder → GPT-2 decoder; autoregressive masked-chunk reconstruction; fixed 22-channel, 79.5M params, pretrained on TUH. Limitation: fixed montage, no frequency/coupling bias.

**BrainBERT (Wang et al. 2023).** Intracranial; tokenizes spectrogram of single electrodes; masked spectrogram reconstruction; transformer. Frequency: spectrogram (time-frequency) but per-electrode, no cross-frequency coupling, no directional operator.

**2025–2026 wave:**
- **CodeBrain (Ma et al. 2025):** TFDual-Tokenizer (independent temporal + frequency encoding) + **state-space model** backbone; decoupled interpretability + multi-scale architecture.
- **BrainOmni (Xiao et al., NeurIPS 2025):** first unified EEG+MEG; BrainTokenizer with Sensor Encoder (spatial layout/orientation/type); discrete quantization.
- **LUNA (Döner et al., NeurIPS 2025, arXiv:2510.22257):** topology-agnostic via learned queries + cross-attention compressing multi-channel EEG to a fixed-size latent; then patch-wise temporal self-attention decoupled from electrode count. Trained on >21,000 hours of TUEG + Siena with masked reconstruction. LUNA-Huge reaches AUROC 0.8957 / AUPR 0.9029 on TUAB ("surpassing most self-supervised baselines and approaching large-scale models like LaBraM and CBraMod") and 0.921 AUROC on TUAR "while reducing FLOPs by 300× and GPU memory consumption by 10×."
- **CSBrain (Zhou et al., NeurIPS 2025):** cross-scale spatiotemporal tokenization + structured sparse attention.
- **Uni-NTFM (Chen et al. 2025):** Heterogeneous Feature Projection (time/frequency/raw streams) + **Dual-domain Cross-attention** (symmetric time↔frequency fusion) + MoE transformer; up to 1.9B params.
- **BandVQ (2025/26 preprint):** per-band VQ-VAE tokenizers (δ,θ,α,β,γ) + shared transformer + masked code prediction + region-based masking + metadata prefix tokens + quantized log-power tokens. Explicit band axis but plain attention and within-band reconstruction.
- **NeuroRVQ / LaBraM++ (Barmpas et al. 2025):** multi-scale residual-VQ codebooks (four parallel temporal branches) + phase-and-amplitude-aware loss (high-fidelity spectral reconstruction).
- **DIVER-0 (Han et al., ICML 2025 Gen-Bio workshop):** full spatio-temporal attention + RoPE (time) + binary attention biases (channel) + Sliding Temporal Conditional Positional Encoding (STCPE) for channel-permutation equivariance.
- **EEGMamba, FEMBA:** Mamba/SSM backbones for efficiency.
- **NeuroLM/UniMind/ELASTIQ:** EEG-as-language LLM approaches.

**Cross-cutting gaps visible in the matrix:** (a) frequency is almost always *inside the tokenizer* or a symmetric cross-attention, never a directionally-mixed axis; (b) all cross-frequency uses are undirected (graph/coherence/cross-attention); (c) no SSL objective forces cross-frequency mechanism learning; (d) montage-agnosticism is now solved several ways (REVE/DIVER-0/LUNA/BrainOmni).

### Part 2 — Transferable ideas from general time-series FMs

- **PatchTST (patching + channel independence):** patching transfers strongly to EEG (all EEG FMs patch). But channel-independence is *wrong* for EEG — inter-channel coupling is physiologically central. **Transfer patching, reject channel-independence.**
- **iTransformer (variate-as-token):** embeds each variate as a token, attention across variates, FFN across time. Partially transferable: EEG's "variate" is an electrode with *spatial montage semantics*, so a pure permutation-invariant variate token discards geometry — REVE's coordinate PE is the EEG-correct fix. Variate-as-token ≈ channel-as-token but must be coordinate-aware.
- **Crossformer (two-stage cross-time then cross-dimension attention):** directly analogous to criss-cross/factorized EEG attention (CBraMod). Transferable and already adopted. Your tri-axial factorization is the 3-axis generalization.
- **TimesNet (2D period-folding):** exploits periodicity via FFT-selected periods reshaped to 2D. Interesting for EEG's oscillatory nature but folds by dominant period, not by physiological bands; **weak transfer vs. explicit band filterbank.**
- **TSMixer (all-MLP axis mixing):** cheap per-axis mixing; philosophically matches "mix each axis with an appropriate operator." Transferable as a lightweight per-axis mixer, but MLP mixing has no mechanistic prior — **your directional coupling operator is the EEG-appropriate replacement for the frequency-axis mixer.**
- **TimesFM / Chronos (decoder-only / quantized tokens, univariate):** forecasting-centric, univariate; quantization loses fine spectral detail. **Weak transfer** — EEG tasks are classification/detection and strongly multivariate.
- **MOMENT (masked reconstruction, multi-task):** MAE recipe transfers; already the EEG default.
- **Moirai (any-variate attention: RoPE time + learned binary variate bias, multi-patch projections):** the any-variate mechanism is exactly what DIVER-0 imported (binary attention biases for channels). Transferable for montage-agnosticism; not a frequency idea.
- **UniTS (unified flattened token, task tokens):** multi-task unification transfers to EEG multi-task FMs (NeuroLM direction); its critique of two-stage factorized attention (that it can't jointly model cross-time×cross-variate) is worth pre-empting for your tri-axial design.
- **TOTEM (self-supervised discrete VQ tokenization):** transfers directly — it is the VQ tokenizer lineage EEG already uses (LaBraM/EEGFormer/BandVQ).
- **SSM/Mamba TS models:** transfer to EEG for long-recording efficiency (EEGMamba, FEMBA, CodeBrain). Efficiency win, not a mechanistic prior.

**Judgment:** general-TS FMs give you patching, factorized cross-dimension attention, any-variate/coordinate spatial handling, and VQ tokenization — all now standard in EEG. None provide a *frequency-mechanism* prior, because general TS has no analog of neural cross-frequency coupling. That absence is precisely your opening.

### Part 3 — Open design gaps / white space (2026)

**(a) Directional cross-frequency coupling / PAC as architectural inductive bias or SSL objective.** Genuinely open. ACCNet (Zhang et al., Neural Networks 2025, S0893608025007336) uses CFC but as *undirected* band-node graph edges ("a cross-frequency coupling mechanism that facilitates the learning of personalised frequency relationships from a node-edge perspective") with symmetric cosine-similarity edges and GAT heads — not directional phase→amplitude, not attention-replacement, and scoped to emotion recognition rather than a foundation model. PAC appears elsewhere only as a hand-crafted input feature (complex-valued PAC + CV-CNN 2023; PAC-based adaptive filters). Directional PAC (transfer-entropy / asymmetric) is established in *analysis* neuroscience but has never migrated into an architecture. **Verdict: uncrowded; publishable white space.** Your MVL-based directional operator (asymmetric, "slow phase gates fast amplitude", differentiable, no atan2) is novel as an operator.

**(b) Coordinate/montage-agnostic spatial encoding.** Crowded: REVE (4D coordinate Fourier PE), DIVER-0 (permutation equivariance + STCPE), LUNA (learned queries), CBraMod (conv-PE), BrainOmni (sensor encoder). **Verdict: not defensible as a headline; adopt as engineering.**

**(c) Tri-axial / factorized space×frequency×time tokenization.** Partially occupied: explicit band axes exist (BandVQ, EEGFormer frequency patches), and space×time factorization is standard (CBraMod, Brant). The specific *three-way* factorization with a distinct operator per axis is uncommon, but factorization per se is not surprising to reviewers. **Verdict: necessary scaffolding, not sufficient novelty alone.**

**(d) SSL objectives that force cross-frequency mechanism learning.** Open. Existing: phase-swap augmentation (learns generic coupling awareness, contrastive), BandVQ band-code masking (within-band), NeuroRVQ phase-aware loss (fidelity), vision-only Masked Frequency Modeling. None deterministically hide HF amplitude and reconstruct from LF phase. **Verdict: uncrowded; this is your strongest, most defensible novelty.**

### Part 4 — Concrete design proposal

**Recommended framing (Design A — the one to publish):** *"Cross-frequency masking: a pretraining objective that forces EEG foundation models to learn directional low-phase→high-amplitude coupling, with a matched directional-coupling operator."*

**One-sentence contribution:** *We show that when the pretraining objective is designed to demand cross-frequency coupling — deterministically masking high-band amplitude and reconstructing it from visible low-band phase — a directional (MVL-based) frequency-axis operator outperforms self-attention, and this mechanism-forcing recipe beats black-box masked-reconstruction scaling on imbalanced clinical EEG tasks.*

**Why now / why it beats black-box scaling:** the field has hit a scaling wall on clinical tasks — AdaBrain-Bench shows FMs "perform comparable or even worse than traditional models" on TUAB/Siena/HMC/Sleep-EDF, and NeuroAtlas shows EEG-FMs don't even reliably beat generic time-series FMs. When brute-force scaling stalls, injecting the *right physiological mechanism through the objective* is the natural next move — and PAC is elevated precisely in seizure onset zones and deep sleep, which is why your objective wins on seizure/abnormality tasks.

- **Tokenization:** tri-axial factorized tokens (electrode × band × time-patch); learnable sinc filterbank (n_bands=8) + differentiable Hilbert → per-(channel,band,patch) phase & amplitude. (SincNet-style learnable bandpass is precedented and interpretable; the tri-axial phase/amplitude token is your scaffold.)
- **Channel/montage:** REVE-style 3D coordinate (x,y,z) Fourier positional encoding (adopt, cite, don't claim as novelty).
- **Positional encoding:** band by center frequency; time by RoPE; space by coordinates.
- **Backbone:** factorized tri-axial encoder — time self-attention O(P²), space self-attention O(C²), **frequency directional-coupling operator O(B²)** (MVL-based, asymmetric, differentiable).
- **Flagship SSL objective:** crossfreq-masking — deterministically hide the entire upper half of bands; reconstruct high-band log-amplitude from visible low-band phase + spatiotemporal context.
- **Ablation contract (the crux):** you MUST run the never-yet-tested 2×2: {freq-mixer ∈ attention, directional-coupling} × {objective ∈ random-MAE, crossfreq-mask}. The flagship claim "coupling > attention *when the objective forces it*" lives in the interaction cell. Also ablate: coupling matrix zeroed vs learned; directional vs symmetrized coupling; n_bands sensitivity; filterbank fixed vs learnable.
- **Target benchmarks:** TUAB, CHB-MIT, TUSZ (your wins — imbalanced binary seizure/abnormal), plus TUEV (6-way) and Sleep-EDF (5-way) where you currently lose — report honestly and analyze *why* (multiclass/stationary tasks may not be coupling-limited).
- **Expected reviewer objections + answers:**
  1. *"Is this just another factorized transformer?"* → No: the frequency axis uses a directional mechanistic operator, and the novelty is the objective×operator interaction (the 2×2 ablation).
  2. *"Supervised PAC layers failed — why believe this?"* → That is the point and the story: report the 3 supervised failures (additive gated bias, attention+gated-PAC-branch, multiplicative coherence gate) as positive evidence that the prior only pays under a mechanism-forcing objective.
  3. *"FMs don't beat supervised on TUAB (AdaBrain/NeuroAtlas/EEG-FM-Audit)."* → Precisely why mechanism-forcing matters; show your PR-AUC wins on imbalanced tasks where black-box scaling stalls, and note EEG-FM-Audit's finding that supervised TS-SEFFNet already matches LaBraM/EEGPT on TUAB.
  4. *"Target leakage in the crossfreq objective."* → You already zeroed the coupling matrix and used freq_mixer=attention during those pretraining runs; document leakage controls and the operator-vs-objective separation.
  5. *"Single seed / partial."* → Run multi-seed, multi-dataset before submission (current results are single-seed on 5 datasets).

**Design B (higher-risk, higher-ceiling):** the same but pretrained at REVE-scale with montage-agnostic coordinates, positioned as a full foundation model. Only pursue if compute allows; otherwise Design A as a focused "objective + operator" methods paper is far more landable.

**Novelty risk assessment:** closest threats are ACCNet (undirected CFC graph — distinguish on directionality + attention-replacement + FM/SSL setting), BandVQ (band axis but plain attention, within-band masking — distinguish on directional operator + cross-band objective), NeuroRVQ (phase-aware fidelity loss, not coupling-forcing), Uni-NTFM (symmetric time/freq cross-attention — distinguish on directionality), EEGFormer (frequency patches but channel-independent, symmetric). None occupy the operator×objective cell. **Risk is moderate and manageable if you foreground the objective and the 2×2 ablation.**

## Recommendations

1. **Commit to the objective-first framing (Design A).** Lead with crossfreq-masking; position the directional operator as "the prior the objective unlocks." This converts your supervised-PAC failures from a liability into the paper's central insight and gives you a clean "why now / why not black-box scaling" narrative.
2. **Immediately run the untested 2×2** (coupling-operator × crossfreq-objective). This is the single most important experiment — the flagship claim is currently unproven because the coupling operator and crossfreq objective have never been run together (you deliberately zeroed the matrix to avoid leakage). If the interaction cell wins, you have a strong paper; if it doesn't, pivot to "crossfreq-masking is an architecture-agnostic objective that beats MAE on imbalanced tasks" (still publishable).
3. **Harden the empirics:** ≥3 seeds, report PR-AUC (not just accuracy/balanced-accuracy) on TUAB/CHB-MIT/TUSZ, and honestly analyze the TUEV/Sleep-EDF losses (hypothesis: multiclass/stationary tasks are less coupling-dependent; consider a task-adaptive masking ratio there).
4. **Adopt, don't claim, montage-agnosticism** (REVE coordinates) and efficiency (optional Mamba/SSM per-axis for long recordings). Cite REVE/DIVER-0/LUNA to pre-empt "spatial handling isn't new" — you concede it and move the contribution to frequency.
5. **Decision thresholds that change the plan:**
   - (a) If the 2×2 interaction is statistically significant across ≥3 datasets → submit as an operator×objective paper to **ICLR/NeurIPS/ICML**.
   - (b) If the operator ties attention but the objective still wins → submit as an **SSL-objective** paper (the operator becomes a secondary contribution / interpretability probe).
   - (c) If crossfreq only wins on seizure/abnormality tasks → reframe as a **clinical seizure/abnormality EEG FM for EMBC/MICCAI**, leaning on the PAC-in-seizure-onset-zone neuroscience.
   - (d) If a scaled baseline (REVE-size MAE) closes your PR-AUC gap on seizure tasks → the "mechanism beats scale" thesis weakens; pivot to interpretability (does the learned coupling matrix recover known theta-gamma / delta-beta PAC?) as the contribution.

## Caveats
- Several cited 2025–2026 works (REVE, NeuroAtlas, BandVQ, Uni-NTFM, LUNA, EEG-FM-Audit, Brain4FMs) are recent preprints or just-accepted; venue/acceptance and exact numbers may shift. Verify final figures before citing in the paper.
- Your positive crossfreq results are single-seed and partial; treat as preliminary until replicated with ≥3 seeds.
- The novelty claim rests on the directionality distinction (directional operator vs undirected graph CFC); reviewers may push on whether your MVL operator is meaningfully "directional" in its *learned* weights — the directional-vs-symmetrized ablation must demonstrate this, ideally with a recovered coupling matrix that matches known physiology.
- Benchmark-overlap and pretrain/test contamination are documented problems in this field (NeuroAtlas; the LaBraM/TUH↔TUAB/TUEV overlap); control for TUH overlap explicitly and state it.
- ACCNet's exact CFC equations could not be read from the paywalled full text; the undirected characterization is inferred from the abstract, PubMed, and the public repo (cosine edges, GAT heads). If ACCNet's camera-ready reveals any directional component, sharpen your distinction to the FM/SSL/attention-replacement setting, which remains uncontested.